textBeforeTable: While the participation rate of Minnesota high school graduates going out of state averages 18 percent; of those who went to college about 28 percent chose to attend out of state within 12 months of high school graduation. Institutions in states bordering Minnesota were the most popular destinations. Sixty-six percent, or 8,377 Minnesota residents going out of state, attended institutions in either Iowa, North Dakota, South Dakota or Wisconsin.   Out-of-State Institutions Attended by Minnesota Residents, 2008   Home > Research, Data & Reports > College Readiness & Participation Data > College Participation Rates > Out-of-State Institutions Attended > Out-of-State Institutions Attended by Minnesota Residents, 2008 Get the latest news in your inbox eNewsletter Sign-up Within My Reach Financing Your Future Financial Aid Basics Paying for College Choosing a College Top Publications Research Reports
textAfterTable: Source: U.S. Department of Education, National Center for Education Statistics, IPEDS enrollment survey. Institutions report the state of residence of freshmen who graduated from high school during the past 12 months. Institutions are required to report these data in even years; while reporting these data in odd years is optional. Therefore, the reported number of Minnesota residents going to college out of state in odd years is usually slightly lower than those in even years.
